<Docs title="Creating Agents">
  <h1>Creating Agents</h1>

  <p>
    Agents are the core building block of the AOS Framework. Each agent has a distinct cognitive
    framework that defines how it thinks, what it values, and where it draws hard lines.
  </p>

  <h2>Scaffold a New Agent</h2>
  <pre><code>aos create agent my-analyst</code></pre>
  <p>This creates <code>core/agents/custom/my-analyst/</code> with starter files.</p>

  <h2>Agent Structure</h2>
  <pre><code>core/agents/custom/my-analyst/
  agent.yaml     # Cognitive framework + config
  prompt.md      # System prompt with template variables</code></pre>

  <h2>agent.yaml Schema</h2>
  <p>Every agent YAML file follows the <code>aos/agent/v1</code> schema:</p>

  <pre><code>schema: aos/agent/v1
id: my-analyst
name: My Analyst
role: "One-sentence description of what this agent does."

cognition:
  objective_function: "What this agent optimizes for"
  time_horizon:
    primary: "30-90 days"
    secondary: "this quarter"
    peripheral: "next year"
  core_bias: data-driven-analysis
  risk_tolerance: moderate
  default_stance: "Show me the data."

persona:
  temperament:
    - "Trait 1"
    - "Trait 2"
  thinking_patterns:
    - "Question this agent asks itself"
  heuristics:
    - name: Rule Name
      rule: "When X, do Y because Z."
  evidence_standard:
    convinced_by:
      - "What persuades this agent"
    not_convinced_by:
      - "What this agent rejects"
  red_lines:
    - "Non-negotiable boundary"

tensions:
  - agent: catalyst
    dynamic: "How this agent's bias conflicts with Catalyst's speed focus"

model:
  tier: standard
  thinking: "off"</code></pre>

  <h2>The Cognitive Framework</h2>

  <h3>Objective Function</h3>
  <p>What the agent optimizes for in every response. This is the single most important field &mdash; it drives all decision-making.</p>

  <h3>Core Bias</h3>
  <p>The intentional bias that colors this agent's analysis. Biases create productive tension when paired against opposing agents.</p>

  <h3>Heuristics</h3>
  <p>Named decision rules the agent applies. Each has a name and a concrete rule. Good heuristics are specific and actionable.</p>

  <h3>Red Lines</h3>
  <p>Non-negotiable boundaries the agent never crosses. These create hard constraints on the agent's recommendations.</p>

  <h2>prompt.md Template</h2>
  <p>The system prompt supports these template variables:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>{"{{agent_name}}"}</code> &mdash; Agent's display name</li>
    <li><code>{"{{agent_id}}"}</code> &mdash; Agent's ID</li>
    <li><code>{"{{session_id}}"}</code> &mdash; Current session ID</li>
    <li><code>{"{{participants}}"}</code> &mdash; Comma-separated agent names</li>
    <li><code>{"{{constraints}}"}</code> &mdash; Constraint summary</li>
    <li><code>{"{{brief}}"}</code> &mdash; The user's brief content</li>
    <li><code>{"{{expertise_block}}"}</code> &mdash; Expertise file configuration</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Tension Pairs</h2>
  <p>
    Define how your agent's bias conflicts with other agents. Tensions create the productive
    disagreement that makes deliberation valuable. The Arbiter can invoke tension pairs to
    deepen the debate.
  </p>

  <h2>Validation</h2>
  <pre><code>aos validate</code></pre>
  <p>Run validation after creating or modifying an agent to ensure schema compliance.</p>
</Docs>
